"Alternative health" is very fun. You read an Indian holistic doctor who talks about all sorts of chakras, spiritual source of sickness, etc., and a paragraph down he mentions "essential fatty acids". He has basically married a wrong paradigm to an obscure spiritual dictionary.

The more radical and pompous the jargon, the ideas, the holisticness, the implication, the more likely it is to just be a regular falsehood prettied up in purple prose. This obviously goes for anything, politics, pseudo-theology and pseudo-metaphysics, literature. Scammers abound
